    {
      "id": "8LK-62PskQbbW2t60HHdX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1433.3981531366946,
      "y": 3832.051771505743,
      "width": 559.41259765625,
      "height": 380,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [
        "Ydh1ipFgVtPKB8AZCgs6B"
      ],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bHO",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 396531229,
      "version": 1676,
      "versionNonce": 1472608883,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1737375397071,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "- Every element of the device is simply a resource with a unique URL\nthat can be used both by people and applications to read and write\ndata\n\n- Now, we put the developer hat on and start building an application\nthat interacts with the WoT device\n    Code: 01.polling-sensor.html\n    Code: 02.polling-sensor-chart.html\n\n- Polling a sensor worked just fine, but this seems somewhat\ninefficient: instead of having to fetch the temperature from the device\nevery 2 seconds, wouldn’t it be better if our code was informed of any\nchange of temperature only when they happen (and if they happen)?\n\n- One of the major impedance mismatches between the model of the\nWeb and the event driven model of IoT applications\n    Solution: WebSockets \n    Code: 03.websockets-temp-graph.html\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "- Every element of the device is simply a resource with a unique URL that can be used both by people and applications to read and write data\n\n- Now, we put the developer hat on and start building an application that interacts with the WoT device\n    Code: 01.polling-sensor.html\n    Code: 02.polling-sensor-chart.html\n\n- Polling a sensor worked just fine, but this seems somewhat inefficient: instead of having to fetch the temperature from the device every 2 seconds, wouldn’t it be better if our code was informed of any change of temperature only when they happen (and if they happen)?\n\n- One of the major impedance mismatches between the model of the Web and the event driven model of IoT applications\n    Solution: WebSockets \n    Code: 03.websockets-temp-graph.html\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
